[2] South America (Argentina)
Date: Wed 25 Jul 2018
Source: Sin Mordaza [in Spanish, trans. edited]
https://www.sinmordaza.com/noticia/532733-los-dos-casos-de-sarampion-detectados-tendrian-el-mismo-origen.html


The 2 cases of measles detected in children in Argentina are of a disease strain "identical to that circulating in other countries of the Americas," according to the National Ministry of Health.

The studies were performed at the Malbrán Institute and indicated that the cases (detected in a 5-month-old baby and a 6-year-old child) have "a common origin," according to preliminary data.

It was officially determined that, according to Malbrán data, "the genotype found in one of the cases is D8 lineage Mvi / Hulu Langat.MYS / 26.11, identical to the strain circulating in other countries in the region."

"So far in 2018, 54 samples have been conclusively matched to the strain identified in the City of Buenos Aires and the reference strain Mvi / Hulu Langat .MYS / 26.11 D8. D," added the health authorities through a statement.

A recent report by the Pan American Health Organization established that this strain is the same one identified in 2017 in Venezuela, a country that is experiencing a serious outbreak of the disease.

While epidemiological studies to determine how the children contracted the virus are underway, the National Ministry of Health issued an alert urging health officials to verify the vaccination status of the population and intensify epidemiological surveillance of vulnerable areas to avoid the reintroduction of the disease.

For her part, Angela Gentile, president of the National Commission for the Elimination of Measles, Rubella and Congenital Rubella in Argentina, reiterated that "the 2 cases are related to each other, which is to say that they probably have a common source."

But according to the specialist, the source of infection "is different from the case of the child that was detected last March [2018]. Since it is a different strain from the one detected in March 2018, we know that the circulation is not endemic."

In Argentina, the vaccine against measles is mandatory, and the national vaccination schedule includes the 1st dose at 12 months (and is repeated at school entry age).

Thus, children aged 12 months-4 years must receive one dose of the trivalent vaccine (measles-mumps-rubella), and those older than 5 must have had 2 doses.

Those born before 1965 do not need to be vaccinated because they are considered protected because they have been in contact with the virus.

"It is important for people to know that the vaccination has a 10% primary failure rate, meaning that if we vaccinate 100 children, there will be 10 who must receive a 2nd dose in order to be protected," Gentile said.

"Adults should also have 2 doses of the vaccine," he added. The last endemic case of measles in Argentina was recorded in 2000.

"Since then, a total of 32 cases have been imported or related to imported carriers. The most recent occurred in the City of Buenos Aires in the epidemiological week 13 (April 2018) of the current year, of which 2 were imported and one related to an imported carrier," they added.

[ProMED-ESP article title translations - Vol 8, Issue 188 - 26 Jul 2018.]

