[3] Argentina (Buenos Aires)
Date: Fri 27 Jul 2018
Source: Pagina12 [machine trans. edited]
https://www.pagina12.com.ar/131199-confirman-un-nuevo-caso-de-sarampion


The Ministry of Health confirmed that a baby of 10 months is the 3rd case of autochthonous measles between the city and the province of Buenos Aires so far this month [July 2018] and 4th during 2018. The cases of a baby of 5 months and a 6-month-old girl reported last week now join the 10-month-old baby who lives in the Buenos Aires town of Quilmes.

This outbreak of the disease puts the health authorities on alert, since the last case of endemic measles was registered in the year 2000. In March of this year [2018], the 1st case was confirmed, in an 8-month-old girl.

The last case "was detected in the epidemiological investigation of the 1st 2 cases, with symptoms beginning at the end of June 2018," reported the team conducted by Adolfo Rubinstein.

"The 3 cases presented compatible symptoms (fever, rash, cough and conjunctivitis) and were confirmed by serology (positive IgM in serum) and viral genome detection by PCR," says the latest epidemiological bulletin released by the government.

In all, the same genotype and lineage were identified: D8 Hulu Langat [see post above], indicated the health authorities, which remarked that "the 3 children recovered favorably." In addition, they emphasized that "control actions focused in the corresponding areas continue, and research is underway to determine the source of infection."

According to reports, after a meeting with the commission of measles experts called by the Ministry of Health, it was decided to launch a new health alert and intensify the epidemiological surveillance of the disease in case of detection in both jurisdictions.

"It is important to remember that measles is very contagious; it is contagious 4 days before and 4 days after the beginning of the eruption, so when a family visits a hospital or health center, mechanisms must be put in place so that they do not have long hours of waiting, but you can quickly identify it, and they can be treated in a separate place depending on each institution," said Angela Gentile, who chairs the National Commission for the Elimination of Measles, Rubella and Congenital Rubella Syndrome in the country.

During the meeting, the commission of experts gave new recommendations to the Minister of Health of the Nation, Adolfo Rubinstein, and to his peers from the City, Ana Bou Pérez, and from the Province, Andrés Scarsi. They include:

Strengthen epidemiological surveillance.
Intensify vaccination actions.
Establish a mechanism for rapid classification (of patients according to suspicious symptoms) in the guards of hospitals and private health centers in the city and province of Buenos Aires.
Maintain the start of the campaign to reinforce the vaccination against measles and rubella for next October [2018].

